I was able to process the two PDFs you uploaded directly in our environment. Using the builtin pdftotext utility, I converted the PDFs to plain text and then formatted them into Markdown, adding a table of contents and inserting chapter headings.

What I produced

  • VolumeI The Sleeping Abductees: converted to Markdown with a TOC at the top. The file is available here: {{file:file-3sf8qeWGifc3fpppwXHJJq}}.
  • VolumeII The Secrets of Amenti: converted to Markdown with its own TOC. The file is available here: {{file:file-6aSUgsdnzykR7FM1DujeH6}}.
  • Sphinx project skeleton: I created a voyagers-docs directory containing a minimal conf.py, an index.md with a table of contents referencing the two books, and both Markdown files in a docs/ subfolder. This can be used as the basis for a Sphinx documentation site. You can download the entire project as a tarball here: {{file:file-MzrJBeD8wUK6SCsB9hm4k6}}.

Next steps

  1. Unpack the voyagers-docs.tar.gz archive. It has this structure:

    voyagers-docs/
  conf.py         Sphinx configuration enabling MyST (Markdown) support
  docs/
    index.md      root page with a toctree linking both volumes
    voyagers1.md  Markdown of VolumeI
    voyagers2.md  Markdown of VolumeII

  2. Install Sphinx and the myst-parser extension locally (e.g., pip install sphinx myst-parser).

  3. From within voyagers-docs, run sphinx-build -b html docs _build/html to generate the static site. You can preview it by opening _build/html/index.html.

  4. Commit the contents of voyagers-docs to your voyagers-md repository on GitHub. Then, on Cloudflare Pages, create a new project pointing to that repository and set the build command to sphinx-build -b html docs _build/html with _build/html as the output directory. Assign your custom domain ReturnOfTheBirdTribes.com in the Pages configuration.

With these steps youll have both books converted to Markdown and a Sphinx site ready to deploy. Let me know if youd like any adjustments to the Markdown formatting or help setting up the deployment.

The files I created exist only in the working environment and were shared with you via the fileIDs above. Youll need to add them to your voyagers-md repository yourself before connecting Cloudflare.

Heres one straightforward way to do that:

  1. Download the tarball or individual Markdown files from the links I provided. Extract the tarball so you have the voyagers-docs folder on your computer.
  2. Clone the repository locally if you havent already:
    git clone https://github.com/HawkEyeTheRapper/voyagers-md.git
cd voyagers-md
  3. Copy the documentation files into the repository:
    # assuming voyagers-docs is alongside the cloned repo
cp -r ../voyagers-docs/* .
    This should place conf.py and the docs/ folder into the root of the repo. Feel free to adjust the layout if you prefer a different directory structure (e.g. keeping everything inside a docs/ folder at the top level).
  4. Commit and push the changes:
    git add .
git commit -m "Add converted Voyagers volumes and Sphinx docs"
git push origin main
    If youre using the GitHub web interface instead of the command line, you can draganddrop the new files into the repository and commit them via the web UI.

Once the repository contains the Sphinx project, you can then go to Cloudflare Pages and create a new project connected to this repo. Configure the build command to run Sphinx (e.g., sphinx-build -b html docs _build/html) and set _build/html as the output directory. Finally, assign your custom domain ReturnOfTheBirdTribes.com in the Pages settings.

Let me know if you need guidance on any of these steps or if you encounter issues during the build or deployment.
